Bar plots is used when you want to show a numerical value (like average, sum, or median) for each category.¶

For bar plots, you need one numerical variable and one categorical variable

Black dot/line is referred as error bars in barsshows a 95% confidence interval for the mean. This means that the black line indicates the range within which the true mean is likely to lie with 95% confidence. These black lines are useful for statistical measures like mean/median. These are not useful for other estimators like sum,min,max. You can ignore those lines for such estimators.

In [6]:
sns.barplot(data=df,x='product_category',y='transaction_qty',estimator='sum') # estimator can be sum,mean,median,min,max 
plt.show()

Violin Plot are the combination of boxplot and kde curves¶

Useful to identify outliers and also understand the distribution of data

To read a violin plot, observe that its width represents the density of data at different values, with wider sections indicating higher frequency or probability of data points. The plot combines elements of a histogram and a box plot. The central box-plot-like element shows the median (a white dot) and the interquartile range (a thick gray bar). Examining the shape and comparing the violins helps understand data distribution and identify differences between groups.

In [32]:
sns.violinplot(data=tips,x='day',y='total_bill')
plt.show()

Swarm Plot is used to show all data points for a categorical variable, while avoiding overlaps.¶

It’s like a scatter plot for categorical data, where points are adjusted so they don’t overlap.

Unlike boxplot or violin plot, which summarize distributions, a swarm plot shows every single data point.

Good for small/medium datasets where you want to see the raw data, not just summaries.

In [33]:
sns.swarmplot(data=tips,x='day',y='total_bill')
plt.show()
In [34]:
sns.swarmplot(data=iris,x='species',y='petal_length')
plt.show()

Heatmaps shows data values as a matrix (2D grid) where values are represented by color intensity.¶

Often used for:

Correlation matrices (to see relationships between variables).

Confusion matrices in ML.

Pivot tables (like Excel cross-tab).
